proof.p:
By Example, elements in O(2) are either rotations of the form
						R_{\theta}
						=
						\begin{pmatrix}
						\cos \theta & - \sin \theta \\
						\sin \theta & \cos \theta
						\end{pmatrix}

					or reflections of the form
						T_{\phi}
						=
						\begin{pmatrix}
						\cos \phi &  - \sin \phi \\
						\sin \phi & \cos \phi
						\end{pmatrix}
						\begin{pmatrix}
						1 & 0 \\
						0 & -1
						\end{pmatrix}
						=
						\begin{pmatrix}
						\cos \phi &  \sin \phi \\
						\sin \phi & - \cos \phi
						\end{pmatrix}.
					Notice that \det(R_{\theta})=1,  \det(T_{\phi})=-1, and T_{\phi}^2=I. We can divide the proof up into two cases. In the first case, all of the elements in G have determinant one. In the second case, there exists at least one element in G with determinant -1.

